and -- tPart 6 Race, Class, and Urban Geographies -- tSteel Industry’s Legacies on the Outskirts of Rio de Janeiro and White Brazilian Capital-State Alliances: A Feminist Approach -- tRio de Janeiro’s Unruly Carbon Periphery: Community Entrepreneurs, Chinese Investors, and the Reappropriation of the Ruins of the COMPERJ Oil Port-and-Pipeline Megaproject -- tFrom Cheap Credit to Rapid Frustration: China and Real Estate in Rio de Janeiro -- tThe China-Ecuador Economic Relationship’s Impact on Unemployment during the Administration of President Moreno -- tPart 7 Hybridity of Transnational Labor -- tSavage Factories of the Manaus Free Trade Zone: Chinese Investments in the Amazon and Social Impacts on Workers -- tNational Development Priorities and Transnational Workplace Inequalities: Challenges for China’s State-Sponsored Construction Projects in Ecuador -- tRio’s Phantom Dubai? Porto do Açu, Chinese Investments, and the Geopolitical Specter of Brazilian Mineral Booms -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book captures an epochal juncture of two of the world's most transformative processes: the People's Republic of China's rapidly expanding sphere of influence across the global south and the disintegration of the Amazonian, Cerrado, and Andean biomes. The intersection of these two processes took another step in April 2020, when Chinese President Xi Jinping launched a "New Health Silk Road" agenda of aid and investment that would wind through South America, extending the Eurasian-African "Belt and Road Initiative" to the Latin American tropics. Through thirty short essays, this volume brings together an impressive array of contributors, from economists, anthropologists, and political scientists to Black, feminist, and Indigenous community organizers, Chinese stakeholders, environmental activists, and local journalists to offer a pathbreaking analysis of China's presence in South America. As cracks in the progressive legacy of the Pink Tide and the failures of ecocidal right-wing populisms shape new political economies and geopolitical possibilities, this book provides a grassroots-based account of a post-US centered world order, and an accompanying map of the stakes for South America that highlights emerging voices and forms of resistance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aInvestments, ChinesezSouth America. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Globalization.2bisacsh  aAsian Diaspora Studies.  aAsian Studies.  aBelt & Road Initiative.  aBrazil.  aChina/PRC.  aEcuador.  aEnvironment.  aExtractivism.  aGender.  aGlobal South.  aGlobal Studies.  aIndigeneity.  aIndigenous Studies.  aInfrastructure.  aInternational Relations.  aLatin American Studies.  aMining.  aPorts.  aRacism.  aSexuality and Feminist Studies.  aSinophobia.  aSocial Movements.  aSouth America.1 aAguiar, Diana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmar, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmar, Paul, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBitencourt, Yasmin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonilla, Emilia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrancoli, Fernando, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrancoli, Fernando, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrito, Cleiton Ferreira Maciel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCamoça, Alana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarpio, Sofía, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChumapi, Israel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular